specialty_summary <- specialty_count %>%
  summarise(
    total_specialties = n(),
    min_count = min(n),
    max_count = max(n),
    mean_count = mean(n)
  )

print(specialty_summary)

              <int>     <int>     <int>      <dbl>
1                40         6      1103       125.

There are 40 total specialties. They do not overlap. They are not evenly distributed because there are about 1103 observations for surgery, compared to the other specialties which are within the 200s-300s.

#Question 2

tokens <- mt_samples %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, transcription)


word_count <- tokens %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE)


top_20_words <- word_count %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 20)

ggplot(top_20_words, aes(x = reorder(word, n), y = n)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Top 20 Most Frequent Words in Transcriptions",
       x = "Word",
       y = "Frequency")

The word âtheâ appeared about 150,000 times. âAndâ appeared around 80,000 times, âwasâ 78,000 times, âofâ 60,000 times, âtoâ 50,000 times, âaâ 45,000 times, âwithâ 40,000 times, âinâ 30,000 times, and the rest are all under 25,000 times. These results show that most of the most frequent words were prepositions or filler words. This makes sense because these words make the structure for most of our sentences

#Question 3

data("stop_words")


tokens_clean <- mt_samples %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, transcription) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words) %>%   # Remove stopwords
  filter(!str_detect(word, "^[0-9]+$"))  # Remove numbers
Joining with `by = join_by(word)`
word_count_clean <- tokens_clean %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE)


top_20_words_clean <- word_count_clean %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 20)

ggplot(top_20_words_clean, aes(x = reorder(word, n), y = n)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Top 20 Most Frequent Words (Excluding Stopwords and Numbers)",
       x = "Word",
       y = "Frequency")

Without the stopwords, the most frequent words are patient, procedure, pain, history. It is clear now that these are medical words

#Question 4 #Bigrams

# Tokenize into bi-grams
bigrams <- mt_samples %>%
  unnest_tokens(bigram, transcription, token = "ngrams", n = 2)

# Count the number of times each bi-gram appears
bigram_count <- bigrams %>%
  count(bigram, sort = TRUE)

# Visualize the top 20 most frequent bi-grams
top_20_bigrams <- bigram_count %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 20)

ggplot(top_20_bigrams, aes(x = reorder(bigram, n), y = n)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Top 20 Most Frequent Bi-grams in Transcriptions",
       x = "Bi-gram",
       y = "Frequency")

The top 4 words included âtheâ from question 2 combined with âpatientâ from question 3. There were even combinations of the top words from question 2, like âof,â âin,â or âtoâ combined with âthe.â

#Question 6

# Load the stopwords dataset
data("stop_words")

# Tokenize the words in the transcription column and remove stopwords
tokens_clean <- mt_samples %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, transcription) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words) %>%   # Remove stopwords
  filter(!str_detect(word, "^[0-9]+$"))  # Remove numbers
Joining with `by = join_by(word)`
# Count the words within each specialty and find the top 5 most used words per specialty
top_words_per_specialty <- tokens_clean %>%
  group_by(medical_specialty, word) %>%
  summarise(word_count = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>%
  group_by(medical_specialty) %>%
  slice_max(word_count, n = 5)

# View the result
